The Kwale government says it has addressed 70 per cent of the issues raised by the EACC since last year.Governor Salim Mvurya said issues of governance, planning and budgeting, asset management, financial management, internal audit and supply chain management have been addressed.He spoke in Diani on Wednesday when he received a report on corruption risk assessment conducted in 2015.The report was presented by Ethics and Anti-Corruption Commissioner Rose Macharia. EACC officials met Mvurya and Deputy Governor Fatuma Achani.Mvurya said, The EACC has been looking at areas where we need to put in place much stronger systems to prevent corruption. Already we have a public participation act, putting up asset register and recruiting an audit committee to strengthen our resolve and make sure our systems work for the people."He welcomed the report, saying it will help the county end corruption. You realise all issues raised by EACC since 2015 when the assessment was done have been handled correctly, he added.He said that his administration is committed to continue to work together with EACC in ensuring executive members, chief officers and directors will make the process of corruption preventing alive and have pro-active way of handling matters.Commissioner Rose Macharia of EACC said that apart from Kwale they have done system review audit to other counties including Kisii, Kericho, Likipia, Nyeri and Vihiga. Our aim is to look at system review is audit for public service sectors. Procurement procedures, revenue, how they work and if they follow the law. We look at systems and ensure we arrest corruption through prevention, he added.She confirmed that Kwale county government has taken measures in mitigating the risks by county government to combat corruption. The EACC said that a survey report on corruption and ethics in devolved services conducted in 2015 which analyzed corruption prone areas by county government singled finance, public service board, procurement, roads, public works, land and infrastructure as most corrupt areas.